  </div>
<div class="indented"><a id="comment-10897"></a>
  <div class="comment">
    <h3 class="title"><a href="/how-stop-people-putting-widescreen-tvs-stretch-mode#comment-10897" class="active">It&#039;s the fault of DVDs</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="/user/brad" title="View user profile." rel="nofollow">brad</a> on Fri, 2009-11-13 17:54.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>DVDs are made either in widescreen anamorphic or in 4:3 mode.  But the TV does not know what sort of DVD is playing, and the DVD player does not know what sort of TV you have unless you go into the menus and tell it.</p>

<p>So to fix that, and the fact that older dvd players did not have a way to be told what sort of tv you had, the tvs needed an aspect ratio switcher, since for an anamorphic widescreen dvd (the best sort of dvd) the stretch is the right thing to do.  However, that is the only time it is the right thing.</p>

<p>The other mode that is handy is zoom mode, for use when watching letterbox movies on TV or DVD.  In that case you want to zoom (perhaps) to make them fill the screen.  The TV could detect that on its own but they often don&#8217;t.</p>

<p>Today, when every dvd player can be told what sort of tv you have (and could make that easy to do in the setup) there is no need for an aspect ratio button.</p>
</div>
    <div class="links">&raquo; <ul class="links"><li class="first last comment_reply"><a href="/comment/reply/506/10897" class="comment_reply">reply</a></li>
</ul></div>
